ASAM SOVD (Service-Oriented Vehicle Diagnostics) 
It is a modern diagnostic protocol (ISO 17978) designed for software-defined vehicles and High-Performance Computers (HPCs). 
It uses REST APIs, HTTP, and JSON to provide flexible, self-describing diagnostic capabilities, moving beyond the limitations of traditional ECU-centered UDS, making it ideal for remote/over-the-air (OTA) diagnostics.

Core SOVD & HiL Concepts
SOVD vs. UDS in HiL: How does the test setup for SOVD differ from traditional UDS?
Answer: Traditional UDS testing focuses on CAN/LIN bus cycles and fixed ODX/CDD databases. SOVD testing requires an Ethernet-based HiL setup (DoIP or standard Ethernet) and tools that can handle REST APIs and JSON payloads rather than raw hex bytes.
Entity Discovery: How do you verify "Self-Description" on an HiL bench?
Answer: You must test that the SOVD server (the ECU/HPC) correctly lists its available "entities" (apps, functions, components) when queried, and that these update dynamically after a software-over-the-air (SOTA) update simulation.
The SOVD Gateway/Adapter: How do you test communication with legacy ECUs?
Answer: You simulate a SOVD-to-UDS adapter. The test case involves sending an HTTP command to the SOVD interface and verifying that the adapter correctly translates this into a UDS request (e.g., Service 0x22) for a simulated or real legacy ECU on the bus. 
